<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-181-596  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 181 596.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  April 10 1989 n243 p47(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Telesphere loses another CEO. (Telesphere International Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Abel, Glenn.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Telesphere International's CEO, Larry Carter, is the fifth seniorofficer to leave Telesphere because of the company's financialproblems, which began with the company's last recorded profit in1982.andP;  Telesphere suffered its worst financial year in 1986, whenit reported a year-end loss of $21.6 million and a negativeworking capital of $19.8 million.andP;  Carter's appointment in May1988 was intended to stop the company's downward trend, but thecompany is expected to show losses in excess of $21 million for1988.andP;  Questionable financial deals are being blamed for thecompany's troubles.andP;  Under a recently announced $15 millionconvertible financing agreement, Francesco Galesi, the company'smajority owner, will purchase Telesphere debentures in exchangefor a 53 percent of the company.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Telesphere International Inc. (management).andO;Ticker:    TSP.andO;Topic:     Financial StabilityChief Executive OfficersResignationManagementReorganization.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Telesphere International's Annual Losses, 1983-1988. (graph)Person:    Carter, Larry (resignation, retirement, etc.).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>